{{Infobox person |name=Eugène Boban |image=EBoban.jpg |image_size= |caption=Eugène Boban at the [[Exposition Universelle (1867)|1867 Paris Exposition]] |birth_name=André Eugène Boban-Duvergé |birth_date=1834 |birth_place= |death_date={{death year and age|1908|1834}} |death_place= |death_cause= |resting_place= |resting_place_coordinates= |residence=Mexico City, Paris, New York City |nationality= |other_names= |known_for=[[crystal skulls]] |education= |employer= |occupation=antiquarian |title= |religion= |spouse= |children= |parents= |relatives= |signature= |website= |footnotes= }}
'''Eugène Boban''' or '''Boban-Duvergé''' (1834–1908) was a French [[antiquarian]]. He was the official archaeologist of the court of [[Maximilian I of Mexico]], and a member of the French Scientific Commission in Mexico. At one time, he held then sold a number of [[crystal skull]]s, one which is now in the [[Musée du Quai Branly]] and another in the [[British Museum]].<ref>Sax ''et al.'' (2008), Walsh (2008)</ref>
==Career== Eugène Boban came to Mexico as a teenager, and became fluent in both Spanish and [[Nahuatl]]. He headed an expedition commissioned by [[Napoleon III]] to collect Mexican art and artifacts, later exhibited at the [[Musée d'Ethnographie du Trocadéro|Trocadéro Museum]] in connection with the [[International Exposition (1867)]]. In 1885 he had published a poster, ''Cuadro arqueológico y etnográfico de la republica mexicana''.<ref>[http://siris-libraries.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!silibraries&uri=full=3100001~!526234~!0#focus Smithsonian Library on-line].</ref> In July 1886, he moved his business to New York City. Two sale catalogues of his collection, catalogued by Ed. Frossard, were published in New York in 1887.<ref>[http://siris-libraries.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!silibraries&uri=full=3100001~!254125~!0#focus Smithsonian Library on-line]</ref> In 1891, he organized and published the Aubin-Goupil Collection of manuscripts, bought in 1889 by [[Eugène Goupil]] and now in the [[Bibliothèque nationale]].
Ethnological objects from his collection were sold in Paris, 1908.<ref>''Préhistorique; ages de la pierre, du bronze, du fer. Catalogue spécial des objets provenant de la collection Eugène Boban et des collections Émile Collin, du Chambon, Gaberel, Landesque, etc.'' Schleicher frères, Paris 1908 ([http://siris-libraries.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?uri=full=3100001~!254125!0 Smithsonian Library on-line])</ref>
==Questions of authenticity== A crystal skull originally sold by Boban, now in the British Museum, has been demonstrated to be a modern fake.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rincon |first=Paul |title=Crystal skulls 'are modern fakes' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7414637.stm | work=BBC News | date=2008-05-23 | accessdate=2010-01-03}}</ref>
==Published works== Boban's published works include: * Eugéne Boban ''Antiquités mexicaines'' Paris, E. Leroux, 1875 * ''Bibliographie palèoethnologique'' 1881 * ''Cuadro arqueológico y etnográfico de la republica mexicana'' Mexico, Imp. de Muriga, 1885 * E. Boban ''Documents pour servir à histoire du Mexique'' Paris, E. Leroux, 1891 *''Histoire de la nation Mexicaine'' 1893
